paragraphs.text: %md ## OML4R Data Transformation: Binning In this notebook, we demonstrate how to bin numerical columns using OML4R. Equi-width and quantile binning are shown. Using the customer insurance lifetime value data set, which contains customer financial information, lifetime value, and whether or not the customer bought insurance, we show how to bin a numerical column and visualize the distribution. msg.data:
OML4R Data Transformation: Binning

In this notebook, we demonstrate how to bin numerical columns using OML4R. Equi-width and quantile binning are shown.

Using the customer insurance lifetime value data set, which contains customer financial information, lifetime value, and whether or not the customer bought insurance, we show how to bin a numerical column and visualize the distribution.

The dataset CUSTOMER_INSURANCE_LTV is generated by the "OML Run-me-first" notebook, which MUST be run before this notebook.

IMPORTANT: The "OML Run-me-first" notebook is available under the menu Templates -> Examples and is a pre-requisite to the current notebook.

Note: If the user plans to use the in-database Naive Bayes algorithm later, Automatic Data Preparation (ADP) performs supervised binning. Supervised binning uses decision trees to create optimal bin boundaries. More details can be found in Naive Bayes

paragraphs.title: Bin salary column into 10 bins
paragraphs.text:
%r

rownames(CUST_DF) <- CUST_DF$CUSTOMER_ID # Ordering rows of CUST_DF for calculation

CUST_BIN_DF <- mutate(CUST_DF, "INCOME_BIN" = cut(CUST_DF$INCOME, breaks=10, dig.lab=7))

paragraphs.title: Plot the distribution of binned income
paragraphs.text:
%r

OUTPUT <- count(CUST_BIN_DF, INCOME_BIN)
rownames(OUTPUT) <- OUTPUT$INCOME_BIN # ordering rows of OUTPUT

output <- ore.pull(OUTPUT) # Pull output ore.frame to data.frame for plotting

output$Bin_INCOME <- factor(output$INCOME_BIN, 
                            levels=c("(37032.5,44556.8]", "(44556.8,52006.6]", 
                                     "(52006.6,59456.4]", "(59456.4,66906.2]", 
                                     "(66906.2,74356]", "(74356,81805.8]", 
                                     "(81805.8,89255.6]", "(89255.6,96705.4]", 
                                     "(96705.4,104155.2]", "(104155.2,111679.5]"))  # Order the output correctly

# output <- output[order(levels(output$INCOME_BIN)),]

barchart(n ~ Bin_INCOME, data = output, horiz = FALSE,
         ylab="Count", scales = list(x = list(rot = 45, relation="free")), col = "blue")

paragraphs.title: Use quantiles for bin boundaries
paragraphs.text:
%r

salary_quantiles <- quantile(CUST_DF$INCOME)

CUST_SET_DF <- transmute(CUST_DF, "INCOME_BIN" = cut(CUST_DF$INCOME, breaks=salary_quantiles, dig.lab=10))

CUST_SET_DF <- count(CUST_SET_DF, INCOME_BIN)
rownames(CUST_SET_DF) <- CUST_SET_DF$INCOME_BIN


cust_set_df <- ore.pull(CUST_SET_DF) # Pull ore.frame to data.frame for plotting

barchart(n ~ INCOME_BIN, data = cust_set_df, horiz = FALSE, ylab = "Count", col =" Blue")
